Sample Data and Generate a Low-Resolution Phase Estimate¶

In [10]:
def partial_fourier(k_sp,upper_or_lower,percentage):
    k_space = k_sp.copy()
    frac = percentage/100
    k_sp_frac = np.empty(k_sp.shape,dtype ='complex')
    start = 0
    end = 0
    
    if upper_or_lower == "up":
        start = 0
        end = int(frac*(int(k_space.shape[0])))
    
    elif upper_or_lower == "lower":
        start = k_space.shape[0]-int(frac*(int(k_space.shape[0])))
        end = k_space.shape[0]
    
    for i in range(start,end):
        k_sp_frac[i,:] = k_space[i,:]
        
    return k_sp_frac
In [11]:
def zero_fill(k_sp,upper_or_lower,percentage):
    k_space = k_sp.copy()
    frac = percentage/100
    k_sp_frac = np.zeros(k_sp.shape,dtype ='complex')
    start = 0
    end = 0
    
    if upper_or_lower == "up":
        start = 0
        end = int(frac*(int(k_space.shape[0])))
    
    elif upper_or_lower == "lower":
        start = k_space.shape[0]-int(frac*(int(k_space.shape[0])))
        end = k_space.shape[0]
    
    for i in range(start,end):
        k_sp_frac[i,:] = k_space[i,:]
        
    return k_sp_frac

Apodization¶

Gibbs artifacts occur as a consequence of using Fourier transforms to reconstruct MR signals into images. In theory, any signal can be represented as an infinite summation of sine waves of different amplitudes, phases, and frequencies. In MR imaging, however, we are restricted to sampling a finite number of frequencies and must therefore approximate the image by using only a relatively few harmonics in its Fourier representation. The Fourier series, then, is cut short or truncated, hence the name for this artifact.

In Partial Fourier acquisitions, high frequency signals which provide the details and edges of the image are lost and a sharp transition of high frequency signal to 0 causes the ringing artifact.

To prevent Gibbs ringing, k-space may be apodized/filtered prior to reconstruction to more smoothly transition from sampled k-space to zero.

  • an optical filtering technique.
  • It is the technical term for changing the shape of a mathematical function, an electrical signal, an optical transmission or a mechanical structure
  • The term apodization is used frequently in publications on Fourier-transform infrared (FTIR) signal processing.

The term apodization is used frequently in publications on Fourier-transform infrared (FTIR) signal processing. Examples of apodization used in the fast Fourier transform analyzer to smooth the discontinuities at the beginning and end of the sampled time record are:

  • 1.3.2.1 Apodizing filter
  • 1.3.2.2 Hann window

Algorithm 2 - Conjugate Synthesis¶

In [46]:
def hermitian_symmetry(k_space):

    # identifying missing points of k-space
    # checks for pints with missing information
    # replaces points with conjugate symmetry based on corresponding points
    
    #check shape
    k_sp = k_space.copy()
    shape = k_sp.shape
    row = int(shape[0])
    mid_row = int(row/2)

    
    for i in range(0,mid_row):
        if all(k_sp[i,:] == ((0+0*1j))):
           k_sp[i,:] = np.conj(np.flip(k_sp[row-i,:]))
    
    for k in range(0,mid_row):
        if all(k_sp[mid_row+k,:] == ((0+0*1j))):
           k_sp[mid_row+k,:] = np.conj(np.flip(k_sp[row-(mid_row+k),:]))
    
    return k_sp
  • One defining feature of Partial Fourier reconstructions is the use of the fact that when your image is purely real (or equivalently, you know the image phase)
  • To get the missing entry, we can simply look at the value in the mirror-symmetric position opposite the origin (A), and conjugate its value to get (A*).
  • In most cases, Partial Fourier is performed along one axis, and the other axis can be fully reconstructed via inverse Fourier Transform, which results in a bunch of independent 1D problems anyway.
  • Let's see what happens when we naively use the conjugate symmetry principle on data that doesn't actually satisfy the constraint of being purely real:

Algorithm 3 - Homodyne/Margosian¶

Without ensuring the image is real, synthesizing conjugate signals from the symmetric locations in k-space clearly produces poor results. In fact, conjugate synthesis without using the phase results in worse reconstruction than zero-filling.

  • To illustrate the importance of the phase correction, cosider the visible up/down symmetry in the phase corrected k-space (right) compared to the original sampled k-space (left):

Steps to applying Algorithm 3¶

  1. Re-weighting the sampled k-space (no explicit conjugating or filling necessary)

  2. Inverse Fourier transforming the re-weighted k-space

  3. Phase correcting the result

  4. Taking the real part of the phase-corrected image as the output

k-space re-weighting can be more generally thought of as a reconstruction spatial filter, and we can take advantage of that to produce a more smoothly varying re-weighting to reduce Gibbs ringing/truncation artefacts:

Smoothed Homodyne Filter¶

In [63]:
# generate re-weighting vector
from scipy import signal
window = signal.gaussian(64, std=7)
window = window/sum(window)
plt.plot(window)
plt.title(r"Gaussian window ($\sigma$=15)")
plt.ylabel("Amplitude")
plt.xlabel("Sample")

filt = np.zeros((128,1))
filt[0:32,:] = 2 # Low
filt[32:96,:] = 1;     # High
padded_filt = np.concatenate((np.ones((64,1))*filt[0],filt,np.ones((64,1))*filt[filt.shape[0]-1]))
filt_1d = np.reshape(padded_filt,(256,))
filt2_1d = np.convolve(filt_1d,window,mode='same')
filt2_1d = filt2_1d[64:192]
filt2 = np.reshape(filt2_1d,(128,1))

Applying Algorithm 3¶

In [66]:
# Smooth Homodyne filtering
reweighted_ksp_3Q_2 = M1_ksp_3Q*filt
# Inverse Fourier Transform
img_rw_2 = np.fft.ifft2(np.fft.fftshift(reweighted_ksp_3Q_2,(0,1)))
# Phase Correction
img_homodyne_2 = img_rw_2*np.conj(phs2)
# Reanl and Non-negative
real_img_homodyne_2 = img_homodyne_2.copy()
real_img_homodyne_2 = np.real(real_img_homodyne_2)
real_img_homodyne_2[real_img_homodyne_2 < 0] = 0
